threat_severity.level_description: Severity MEDIUM because it was considered trojan.

attributes.magic: ELF 64-bit LSB pie executable, x86-64, version 1 (SYSV), dynamically linked, interpreter /lib64/ld-linux-x86-64.so.2, BuildID[sha1]=ac6a29221cc57ca29c089de8428ad13a30b2be8c, for GNU/Linux 3.2.0, stripped

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: The analyzed ELF binary is a specialized Remote Access Trojan (RAT) or backdoor designed for remote command execution and file manipulation. It supports both direct-connect and 'connect-back' (reverse shell) modes. Key malicious features include: 1) Remote Shell Access: The 'sub_407a20' function sets up an interactive shell environment by manipulating terminal attributes (tcsetattr/ioctl) and executing 'exec bash --login'. 2) Encrypted Exfiltration: It implements custom cryptographic routines (sub_4040af, sub_404e75) for network communication, likely a block cipher and hashing for authentication. 3) File Transfer: Functions 'sub_407858' (put) and 'sub_40767d' (get) provide bidirectional file transfer capabilities. 4) Password Protection: It uses 'getpass' to require authentication before granting access, characteristic of persistent backdoors.
